08040nam a22010335i 9780812201031DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132003pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122010317 a10.9783/97808122010312doi  a(DE-B1597)448956  a(OCoLC)979630796  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD1750b.F54 2003 7aSOC0260202bisacsh04a338.1/097322100aFighting for the Farm :bRural America Transformed /ced. by Jane Adams. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 Introduction -- tPart I North American Agriculture in the World System: Overview and Case Studies -- t2 The Social Economy of Development: The State of/and the Imperial Valley -- t3 From the National Policy to Continentalism and Globalization: The Shifting Context of Canadian Agricultural Policies -- t4 The Contested Terrain of Swine Production: Deregulation and Reregulation of Corporate Farming Laws in Missouri -- t5 The Contingent Creation of Rural Interest Groups -- tPart II Foundations of Twentieth Century U.S. Policy -- t6 The Origin of the Federal Farm Loan Act: Issue Emergence and Agenda-Setting in the Progressive Era Print Press -- t7 Low Modernism and the Agrarian New Deal: A Different Kind of State -- t8 The New Deal Farm Programs: Looking for Reconstruction in American Agriculture -- t9 The U.S. Farm Financial Crisis of the 19805 -- tPart III The Political Implications of Daily Life -- t10 The Entrepreneurial Self Identity and Morality in a Midwestern Farming Community -- t11 Considerably More Than Vegetables, a Lot Less Than Community: The Dilemma of Community Supported Agriculture -- tPart IV The Politics of the Environment -- t12 Canadian Agricultural Policy Liberal, Global, and Sustainable -- t13 Constructing Genetic Engineering in the Food and Fiber System as a Problem: Urban Social Movement Organizations as Players in Agricultural Discourse -- t14 Eating in the Gardens of Gaia Envisioning Polycultural Communities -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn North America industrial agriculture has now virtually displaced diversified family farming. The prevailing system depends heavily on labor supplied by migrants and immigrants, and its reliance on monoculture raises environmental concerns. In this book Jane Adams and contributors—anthropologists and political scientists among them—analyze the political dynamics that have transformed agriculture in the United States and Canada since the 1920s. The contributors demonstrate that people become politically active in arenas that range from the state to public discourse to relations between growers and their contractors or laborers, and that politics is a process that is intimately local as well as global.The farm financial crisis of the 1980s precipitated rapid consolidation of farms and a sharp decline in rural populations. It brought new actors into the political process, including organic farmers and environmentalists. Fighting for the Farm: Rural America Transformed considers the politics of farm policy and the consequences of the increasing alignment of agricultural interests with the global economy. The first section of the book places North American agriculture in the context of the world system; the second, a series of case studies, examines the foundations of current U.S. policy; subsequent sections deal with the political implications for daily life and the politics of the environment.Recognizing the influence of an array of political constituencies and arenas, Fighting for the Farm charts a decisive shift since the early part of the twentieth century from a discursive regime rooted in economics to one that now incorporates a variety of environmental and quality-of-life concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAgriculture and statezUnited States. 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszCanada. 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszNorth America. 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszUnited States. 4aAmerican History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh  aAgriculture.  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aBusiness.  aEconomics.  aPublic Policy.1 aAdams, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarnett, Barry J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConstance, Douglas H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLind, Laura B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDudley, Kathryn Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedmann, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilbert, Jess, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalf, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleine, Anna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnuttifa, K. Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReisner, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRikoon, J. Sanford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRudy, Alan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShulman, Stuart W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSummers, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWells, Miriam J., econtributor.4ctb4htt